%h2 Layout

%h4 Grid System

%p The grid may be divided into <code>whole</code>, <code>halfs</code>, <code>thirds</code>, <code>fourths</code>, <code>fifths</code>, <code>sixths</code>, <code>eighths</code>, <code>tenths</code>, and <code>twelths</code>.

%p Each division comes with a set of classes <code>[.]</code> to identify the different widths. These classes may be used on an element directly or as an extend by way of the <code>@extend</code> rule. Class names may be singular or plural depending on how many columns you wish to span. For example, when creating a six column grid you may define an element that spans a single column with the class <code>.grid-one-sixth</code> or you may define an element that spans four columns with the class <code>.grid-four-sixths</code>.

%p Using a class to define the width alone will not create a grid system. Rows, or multiple rows, need to be wrapped in an element with the <code>.grid</code> class and elements with the defined width need to include the <code>.grid-col</code> class. Take the following example:

%pre
  %code
    :preserve
      &lt;div class="grid"&gt;
        &lt;div class="grid-col grid-one-third"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;div class="grid-col grid-two-thirds"&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;

